<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-829-246  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 829 246.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Sept 1 1990 v29 n17 p94(11).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How much can design-for-test reduce the need for testing?andO;(includes related article on JTAG IEEE-1149.1 standard)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gabay, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Engineers usually design, debug and implement circuits first andthen devise a test strategy.andP;  Working out a test strategy at thesame time as product conception and definition eliminatesunnecessary design iterations and enables test engineers to worktogether with design engineers, printed circuit board designersand software programmers.andP;  Test features can then be incorporatedat the time of implementation.andP;  Hardware engineers are ultimatelyresponsible for creating a design that can be tested, and theirchoice of parts can affect the outcome.andP;  Every type of device hasits own problems regarding testing and testability.andP;  There aretools to help with testing of problems in such areas asprogrammable logic devices and semicustom silicon.andP;  Severaltesting tools for a variety of devices are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Circuit DesignTestingBoards-CardsElectrical Engineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   The ideal design-for-test project flow. (chart)Boundary scan vs. full scan. (chart)Oki's scan-test flip-flops. (chart)Crosscheck's embedded matrix. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>